{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17631372","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17631372"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T17:26:22+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T17:26:22+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17367"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"17367","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/17367"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10057"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"70205"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"10057","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/10057"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17367"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"55669"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"4948"},{"type":"tags","id":"5363"},{"type":"tags","id":"5395"},{"type":"tags","id":"7844"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"23548"},{"type":"contributions","id":"23561"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"70205","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/70205"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA new screening program for thyroid cancer is implemented. Before screening, patients were typically diagnosed when they developed neck symptoms and survived an average of three years after diagnosis. With screening, patients are diagnosed two years earlier and survive an average of five years after diagnosis.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the actual survival benefit of this screening program?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Five year improvement in survival time","No improvement in actual survival time","Eight year improvement in survival time","Three year improvement in survival time","Two year improvement in survival time"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis question illustrates \u003Cstrong\u003Eno improvement in actual survival time\u003C/strong\u003E due to lead time bias. While it appears that survival has improved from three to five years after diagnosis, the screening simply detected cases two years earlier without changing the natural history of disease. The total time from disease onset to death remained the same.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003ETo determine if a screening program truly improves outcomes, we must account for lead time bias by measuring survival from the actual onset of disease, not just from the time of diagnosis. In this case, patients died at the same time point whether they were screened or not.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Lead time bias occurs when screening appears to improve survival by detecting disease earlier, without actually changing the natural history or outcome.","Lead time bias can make screening programs appear effective even when they do not actually extend life.","True improvements in survival must be measured from time of diagnosis to death plus account for lead time bias."],"references":["Sullivan LM. Essentials of biostatistics in public health. 3rd ed. Burlington (MA): Jones \u0026 Bartlett Learning; 2018.","Dawson B, Trapp RG. Basic \u0026 clinical biostatistics. 4th ed. New York: McGraw-Hill; 2004.","Lee CI, Elmore JG. Beyond survival: a closer look at lead-time bias and disease-free intervals in mammography screening. JNCI: Journal of the National Cancer Institute. 2024;116(3):343-4. Available at: https://academic.oup.com/jnci/article/116/3/343/7493508"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"55669"}},"question":{"data":{"type